<br />
<br />
--Terrible and evil by Manuel Cabezalí--<br />
<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Does anyone remember old Trust Me days?<br />
<br />
I do.<br />
<br />
At last Decipher has made a decent CC counter, and a useful card in many other ways. This and the new Arwen makes this deck viable.<br />
<br />
First of all, I must remeber you the benefits of playing a trust me deck:<br />
<br />
·You have GREAT skirmishing power, relying on companions, weapons, events and conditions.<br />
<br />
·You have significant direct damage with Aragorn&#8217;s bow, Terrible and Evil and Legolas.<br />
<br />
·You have the best condition removal in the game.<br />
<br />
·You have good burden removal with Sam and Narya.<br />
<br />
·And you have a nice and funny deck to play.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now on the strategy:<br />
<br />
I usually bid 0-2. Start Arwen and Gimli. Going first is nice but not indispensable, since Nazgûl can get one or two stops easily in the early game. After that, take your time to setup. Running too much on the early game can mean losing important companions between sites 4-6. Once the FP is setup, it is unstoppable.<br />
<br />
ALWAYS ALWAYS ALWAYS hold a Terrible and Evil in your hand. Did I say you have to hold it ALWAYS?<br />
<br />
Your main companions are Gimli, Arwen, Frodo, Gandalf and Aragorn.<br />
<br />
·Gimli is the only companion who is damage +2 with axe, provides orc protection and is money against big damage +1 minions with his helm.<br />
<br />
·Arwen is a beast. <br />
<br />
·Aragorn provides protection against swarms, shoots people and is a solid fighter.<br />
<br />
·Gandalf is the key of the deck. He&#8217;s the strongest companion and you should never put him in risk.<br />
<br />
·Legolas is there as a backup. Also good against Moria and Dunland and everything, I guess.<br />
<br />
·Sam is there for burden removal and for catching the ring.<br />
<br />
<br />
Card choices:<br />
<br />
·Old Gimli&#8217;s helm over Gimli&#8217;s armor: I already have enough cards that need to discard others to work (moment of respite, gwemegil) and that could make me lose initiative...<br />
<br />
·Old Asfaloth over new Asfaloth: Simply because of the new site path. Many plains and no undergound.<br />
<br />
·Ranger&#8217;s sword over Anduril (both versions): I discard the one that makes gorn def+1 because there are SO many ways to add threaths and I need the damage +1 bonus. The other one because I need the bow (mostly because of the ausence of Legolas in the starting FP) and I haven&#8217;t got any useful sites 3 or 6.<br />
<br />
·Shadowfax over Glamdring: Basically because none of my companions is able to handle Cantea FOTR. I know shadowfax is discarded by Uruk spears but Uruks suck anyway in the new environment, so that doesn&#8217;t bother me. Terrible and Evil also helps.<br />
<br />
·Narya over Staff: Because of the cost and the burden removal, wich is necessary against those ever threaten easterlings.<br />
<br />
·3 SOTSF: Well, they are more like 4. I count Barlinman as a possible SOTSF or GST.<br />
<br />
·Moment of respite: Due to all the Gandalf exertions that this deck requires I need some additional way to heal him. Also, cycling is good I hear :)<br />
<br />
·Terrible and evil: The key-card. It prevents you from Grima and everything that acts on the maneuver phase. It also owns Nazgûl and everything really. Broken card in my opinion.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
FP Matchups:<br />
<br />
Nazgûls: Arwen and Gandalf with trust me and SOTSF should own them. Terrible and evil also helps.<br />
<br />
Moria: GST, dreary, ROTN, Greenleaf, and in some cases Terrible and evil helps a lot. Insurgents hurt but Frodo has lots of protection in this deck. This deck is very vulnerable to saruman snows, so that&#8217;s why Dreary is so important.<br />
<br />
Uruks: I really don&#8217;t see them much played, since there are no battlegrounds. But if someone plays them, trust me owns them. Terrible and evil for the spears if they want to dicth shadowfax. Trackers have their nemesis in Arwen. Uruk archery might be a bit tough, but Dreary and IB helps a lot at this point.<br />
<br />
Dunland: I don&#8217;t see many people playing them, but I still have to playtest. I suposse that the main idea should be having more strenght than them, wich is pretty possible with trust me.<br />
<br />
Sauron: Well, I still have to find a decent Sauron shadow... GST owns them, I guess...<br />
<br />
Easterings: Decent burden removal is the key.<br />
<br />
Southrons: Still have to playtest, but I think that winning skirmishes should help ;-)<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Now let&#8217;s go on the shadow!<br />
<br />
I&#8217;ve choosen old FOTR nazgûl over the new ROTK mainly because they look more reliable to me and get the stops my FP need to setup. And because I don&#8217;t own many of them ;)<br />
<br />
Card choices:<br />
<br />
·Pale Blade x2: I need condition removal. And I need my witch kings as big as possible. <br />
<br />
·No Morgul Gates: Since the most popular way of choke is DH, it seems a bit retarded to add Morgul gates. And to be honest, I don&#8217;t own any :-p (now you see how poor I am)<br />
<br />
·Morgul detachment: The guy to play with a Witch King. I&#8217;m still testing it, but the looks of a 15 fierce damage +1 guy for 7 seems impressive.<br />
<br />
·Black steeds: With all those plains sites it seems quite obvious, I guess...<br />
<br />
·Relentless Charge: Although it may look questionable, this card owns Dauntless Hunter.<br />
<br />
·Not easily destroyed: LAUGH! YEAH! LAUGH! My friend Miguel Tarín Vegas suffered this card in Essen when playing Rohan. A verty versatile card, this card owns Rohan and Eomer particularly. If you don&#8217;t believe me, then play it. Also kills FPs that have 6 companions and only Eowyn LOR as protection. <br />
<br />
Shadow matchups:<br />
<br />
Rohan: Possibly the hardest matchup, you should prepare to run. BB/BT with Wormtongue help in crucial sites, as well as not easily destroyed, wich can kill people (trust me)<br />
<br />
DH: Don&#8217;t play one Nazgûl per site. That&#8217;s the way you lose to DH. Keep your twilight for their double move. They can handle one nazgûl easily but it becomes quite difficult when there are 2 or 3 of them. A well timed Relentless Charge will help, too.<br />
<br />
Other FPs: RB rangers find problems with Nazgûls and Ferny. Ents too. The rest of FPs doesn&#8217;t look so popular. I might be forgetting something, anyway...<br />
<br />
<br />
Well, I think that covers it all. Thanks for reading.<br />
<br />
Manuel.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
